    "James W. Knox": "where their mouth devours households. Combining the two gives a graphic picture. Does this verse explain the strange statement in 1 Corinthians 15:32? 1:12 \u2013 Slow bellies. This verse expands the reference to filthy lucre. Their unwillingness to labor with their hands led them to acquire wealth through illegitimate means. 1:13 \u2013 Wherefore. Because of their character. 1:13 \u2013 Rebuke them sharply. See\nverse 11 and comments. The firm treatment used in dealing with false teachers is also to be used with those within the church in an attempt to teach and to train them to overcome the inherent failures of their nature and ungodly behavior learned from their ungodly society. Through many years of working with new creatures (2 Corinthians 5:17), I am convinced the Holy Spirit does not bring about a change in personality. Hard-working men get saved and become hard-working saved men. Submissive women get saved and become submissive saved women. Lazy men get saved and become lazy saved men. I have not known one case in a thousand where the personality was changed at the new birth. This explains why so much of the New Testament epistles are taken up with instructing the believer to overcome HIMSELF. God knew what kind of man Saul was, counting him faithful [v_1Ti_1_12] before putting him into the ministry (1 Timothy 1:12). To be effective in a ministry, whether Titus\u2019 on Crete or ours in the city where we live or on the mission field to which we are travelling, one must understand the makeup of the people with whom he is dealing. 1:13 \u2013 That they may be sound in the faith. \u2013 This is to be the motive behind the sharp rebuke. If the motive is improper, those who need the correction will never receive it. The sharpest reproofs must be given for the good of the reproved. There is a great need for spiritual leaders to stand authoritatively on the precepts of scripture. Our society, public education system, and entertainment world are perverted by a theory of moral relativity. All is wishy-washy. Nothing is absolute. The people on the streets, in their churches, and in their homes are in desperate need of something solid and certain. The children in our society are crying out for loving discipline. Spiritual babes in the churches are crying out for the same. They need to have sin pointed out and named. They need to have doctrines set forth with all certainty. 1:14 \u2013 Not giving heed to Jewish fables. Traditions, fairy-tales, fables, and commandments of men are not sound doctrine and should not be heeded. We have also a more sure word of prophecy [v_2Pe_1_19] (2 Peter `[char_Peter_Mat_4]` 1:19), so do not follow cunningly devised fables (2 Peter `[char_Peter_Mat_4]` 1:16). The commandments of men were rebuked as tradition by [v_Mat_15_9] Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` (Matthew 15:9; Mark 7:9) and are called doctrines of devils in [v_1Ti_4_1] 1 Timothy 4:1. 1:14 \u2013 That turn from the truth. This is the end result of replacing sound Bible doctrine with fables or traditions. What do the following have in common? \u00b7 Good Friday \u00b7 the three wise men \u00b7 two of every animal on Noah `[char_Noah_Neh_6]`\u2019s ark \u00b7 Mary `[char_Mary_Ref]` riding a donkey \u00b7 business meetings in the church \u00b7 Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` born on December 25 \u00b7 Eve `[char_Eve_Ref]` eating an apple \u00b7 Saul falling from his horse on the Damascus Road \u00b7 infant baptism \u00b7 Jewish feasts and holy days practiced by the New Testament church If you answered, \u201cThey are taught as truth but are not to be found in the Bible,\u201d you answered correctly. You cannot turn to a fable without turning from the truth. You cannot endorse human tradition without insulting the words of the Lord. 1:15 \u2013 Unto the pure all things are pure: but unto them that are defiled and unbelieving is nothing pure; but even their mind and conscience is defiled. The end of this great verse shows that we are dealing with the root and not the fruit. The defiled and unbelieving are without purity. Their mind and conscience are defiled. In the days of Noah `[char_Noah_Neh_6]`, God saw that the wickedness of man was great in the earth, and that EVERY imagination of the thoughts of [v_Gen_6_5] his heart was ONLY evil continually (Genesis 6:5). The third chapter of Romans makes plain that man has not changed since that day. The unbeliever cannot receive the things of [v_1Co_2_14] the Spirit of God (1 Corinthians 2:14). Chrysostom stated, \u201cGod made nothing impure.\u201d The impurity of man\u2019s heart and his defiled conscience lead him to perceive things in an improper manner. The human body, the computer, hops and barley, the tape recorder \u2013 each are used in a myriad of ways depending not on their innate goodness or evil but upon the heart condition of the one using them. The first half of",
    "Warren W. Wiersbe": "Christians are established by the truth, which explains why Paul `[char_Paul_Act_13]` wrote this letter: to explain God\u2019s plan of salvation to Christians so they would be established, and so they would share the truth with the lost. After all, we cannot really share with others something we do not have ourselves. This means that our own study of Romans should make us more stable in the faith, and more excited to share Christ with others. And the result? \u201cTo God only wise, be glory through Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` Christ for ever.\u201d QUESTIONS FOR PERSONAL REFLECTION OR GROUP DISCUSSION"
